```c
uint16_t htons(uint16_t x) {
    return (x >> 8) | (x << 8);
}

uint32_t htonl(uint32_t x) {
    return ((x >> 24) & 0xFF)       |
           ((x >> 8)  & 0xFF00)     |
           ((x << 8)  & 0xFF0000)   |
           ((x << 24) & 0xFF000000);
}
```

**Endianness:**
- **Big-endian (network byte order):** MSB first — `0x1234` stored as `12 34`
- **Little-endian (ARM, x86):** LSB first — `0x1234` stored as `34 12`

**Why it matters:** Protocol headers (TCP/IP, CAN, Modbus) define byte order. If your MCU is little-endian (most ARM Cortex-M) and the protocol is big-endian, you must swap.

