questions.answer:
**The virtual function problem in embedded:**
Virtual functions use a vtable — a pointer per object (4-8 bytes) plus an indirect call at runtime. On a Cortex-M with a tight loop calling a virtual function millions of times, the indirect branch kills branch prediction and adds latency. More importantly, the compiler can't inline virtual calls.

---

**Classic virtual approach:**
```cpp
class Uart {
public:
    virtual void write(const uint8_t* data, size_t len) = 0;
    virtual int  read(uint8_t* buf, size_t len) = 0;
    virtual ~Uart() = default;
};

class Uart1 : public Uart {
public:
    void write(const uint8_t* d, size_t n) override { /* HW specific */ }
    int  read(uint8_t* buf, size_t n) override      { /* HW specific */ }
};

// Problem: every call is indirect — no inlining possible
void send_packet(Uart& uart, Packet& pkt) {
    uart.write(pkt.data, pkt.len);  // vtable lookup, indirect call
}
```

---

**CRTP approach (zero runtime overhead):**
```cpp
// Base class is a template parameterized on the derived class
template<typename Derived>
class UartBase {
public:
    // Dispatch to derived at COMPILE TIME — no vtable
    void write(const uint8_t* data, size_t len) {
        static_cast<Derived*>(this)->write_impl(data, len);
    }
    int read(uint8_t* buf, size_t len) {
        return static_cast<Derived*>(this)->read_impl(buf, len);
    }

    // Common behavior using the interface — gets inlined
    void write_string(const char* s) {
        write(reinterpret_cast<const uint8_t*>(s), strlen(s));
    }
};

class Uart1 : public UartBase<Uart1> {
    friend class UartBase<Uart1>;
private:
    void write_impl(const uint8_t* d, size_t n) {
        // Direct HW register access — will be INLINED by optimizer
        for (size_t i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            while (!(UART1->SR & TXNE)) {}
            UART1->DR = d[i];
        }
    }
    int read_impl(uint8_t* buf, size_t n) { return 0; }
};

// Template function — fully resolved at compile time, everything inlined
template<typename UartT>
void send_packet(UartBase<UartT>& uart, const Packet& pkt) {
    uart.write(pkt.data, pkt.len);  // Resolved at compile time, inlined
}
```

---

**Assembly comparison:**
```
Virtual call:
  LDR  r3, [r0, #0]        ; load vtable pointer
  LDR  r3, [r3, #8]        ; load function pointer from vtable
  BLX  r3                   ; indirect call (no prediction, no inlining)

CRTP inlined:
  (function body directly inlined — 0 call overhead, 0 branch)
```

---

**Trade-offs:**

| | Virtual | CRTP |
|---|---|---|
| Runtime polymorphism | Yes | No (type fixed at compile time) |
| Inlining | No | Yes |
| vtable overhead | 4-8 bytes/object | None |
| Code size | One copy | One copy per type instantiation |
| Runtime type selection | Yes (pointer/reference) | No — use `std::variant` |
| Readability | Familiar | Confusing to CRTP newcomers |

**When to use CRTP in embedded:**
- HAL abstraction layers (compile-time choice of UART1, UART2, SPI1...)
- Protocol encoders with configurable transports
- Sensor driver libraries where transport (I2C vs SPI) is a template parameter
- Policy-based design (clock policy, checksum policy as template params)

```cpp
#include <cstdint>
#include <cstddef>
#include <cstring>
#include <utility>
#include <cassert>

// DMA buffers must be aligned for cache coherency on Cortex-M7
constexpr size_t DMA_ALIGN = 32;  // 32-byte D-cache lines

class DmaBuffer {
public:
    explicit DmaBuffer(size_t capacity)
        : data_(static_cast<uint8_t*>(aligned_alloc(DMA_ALIGN, capacity))),
          capacity_(capacity), size_(0)
    {
        assert(data_ != nullptr);
    }

    ~DmaBuffer() { free(data_); }

    // Non-copyable: copying would require new DMA-aligned allocation + memcpy
    DmaBuffer(const DmaBuffer&) = delete;
    DmaBuffer& operator=(const DmaBuffer&) = delete;

    // Move constructor: transfer ownership, zero-copy
    DmaBuffer(DmaBuffer&& other) noexcept
        : data_(other.data_), capacity_(other.capacity_), size_(other.size_)
    {
        other.data_     = nullptr;
        other.capacity_ = 0;
        other.size_     = 0;
    }

    // Move assignment
    DmaBuffer& operator=(DmaBuffer&& other) noexcept {
        if (this != &other) {
            free(data_);
            data_           = other.data_;
            capacity_       = other.capacity_;
            size_           = other.size_;
            other.data_     = nullptr;
            other.capacity_ = 0;
            other.size_     = 0;
        }
        return *this;
    }

    uint8_t* data()        { return data_; }
    size_t   size() const  { return size_; }
    size_t   capacity() const { return capacity_; }
    bool     valid() const { return data_ != nullptr; }

    void set_size(size_t n) { assert(n <= capacity_); size_ = n; }

private:
    uint8_t* data_;
    size_t   capacity_;
    size_t   size_;
};

// Zero-copy TX pipeline
void dma_start_tx(DmaBuffer buf) {
    // Takes ownership — buf destroyed at end of function after DMA completes
    // In real code: program DMA registers, pass to completion callback
    printf("DMA TX: %zu bytes from %p\n", buf.size(), (void*)buf.data());
}

void send_telemetry(const uint8_t* payload, size_t len) {
    DmaBuffer buf(256);

    // Fill the buffer in-place (no intermediate allocation)
    memcpy(buf.data(), payload, len);
    buf.set_size(len);

    // Move into DMA — zero bytes copied, ownership transferred
    dma_start_tx(std::move(buf));
    // buf is now empty (data_ == nullptr) — safe to destruct
}
```

**Why move semantics matter here:**
- DMA buffers must be DMA-capable (aligned, possibly in specific SRAM region)
- Copying them defeats the purpose of zero-copy DMA
- With move semantics: the buffer travels through the pipeline — encode → compress → transmit — with **zero copies**
- The `= delete` on copy makes the intent explicit: this buffer is a unique resource

**The moved-from state rule:** After `std::move(buf)`, `buf` is in a valid but unspecified state. Our implementation sets `data_ = nullptr` and `size_ = 0`, so `valid()` returns false — easy to check in debug assertions.

